Airbnb Geospatial Analysis: Best Areas for Investment¶

This project aims to identify the most profitable areas for Airbnb investment by analyzing price trends, demand, and spatial clustering using machine learning and geospatial techniques.

Data Preprocessing¶

Handling Missing Data¶

The dataset contained missing values in reviews_per_month, which was replaced with 0 (assuming no reviews). The properties with missing names were also dealt with, by giving them "No name" as a value since that will not be significant for this analysis

In [124]:
df = pd.read_csv("AB_NYC.csv")
missing_values = df.isnull().sum()

df = df.assign(
    reviews_per_month=df["reviews_per_month"].fillna(0),
    last_review=df["last_review"].fillna("No reviews"),
    name=df["name"].fillna("No name"),
    host_name=df["host_name"].fillna("No host name")
)

missing_values = df.isnull().sum()
print(missing_values)

Handling Outliers¶

The dataset contains extreme values for the price column, which will be dealt with by removing the top 1% of the data.

In [125]:
lower_bound = df["price"].quantile(0.01)  # Bottom 1%
upper_bound = df["price"].quantile(0.99)  # Top 1%

df = df[(df["price"] >= lower_bound) & (df["price"] <= upper_bound)]

Correlation HeatMap¶

correlation_matrix = df.corr(numeric_only=True)

# Create a heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap="coolwarm", fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)

# Add labels and title
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap of Airbnb Features")
plt.show()

1. Price vs. Availability

  • Low correlation between price and availability_365.
  • This suggests pricing does not strongly influence how often a listing is available.

2. Price vs. Number of Reviews

  • Negative correlation between price and number_of_reviews/reviews_per_month.
  • This implies cheaper listings tend to receive more reviews, possibly due to higher affordability and demand.

3. Reviews per Month vs. Availability Some positive correlation between reviews_per_month and availability_365.

  • Listings that are more available tend to get more reviews, indicating they are booked frequently.

Overall no strong correlations between the variables

# median price per neighborhood
neighborhood_price = df.groupby("neighbourhood")["price"].median().reset_index()
neighborhood_price = neighborhood_price.sort_values(by="price", ascending=False)

# reviews per month as a proxy for demand
neighborhood_demand = df.groupby("neighbourhood")["reviews_per_month"].mean().reset_index()
neighborhood_demand = neighborhood_demand.sort_values(by="reviews_per_month", ascending=False)

# Merge price and demand data
neighborhood_data = pd.merge(neighborhood_price, neighborhood_demand, on="neighbourhood")

# Display DataFrame as a formatted string
neighborhood_data.to_string(index=False)

Calculating Key Metrics Median price per neighborhood was calculated to identify high-priced areas. Average reviews per month per neighborhood were used as a proxy for demand (higher reviews → more bookings)

Understanding the Spatial Distribution of Prices¶

To identify high-value investment areas, we created a heatmap representing the spatial distribution of Airbnb prices across NYC. The warmer (red) areas indicate higher-priced listings, while cooler (blue) areas correspond to lower-priced listings.

Key Observations from the Price Heatmap:

  • Manhattan exhibits the highest concentration of expensive listings, particularly in Midtown, Tribeca, and SoHo.
  • Brooklyn and Queens have a mix of mid-range and budget listings, with prices dropping significantly as we move away from the city center.
  • Areas in Staten Island and the Bronx have significantly lower prices, making them less attractive for premium Airbnb investments.

Clustering Airbnb Listings for Investment Insights¶

We applied K-Means Clustering to categorize listings into three investment-friendly clusters based on location and price. Each listing was assigned a cluster label (0, 1, or 2):

What Do the Clusters Mean?¶

  • Cluster 0 (Budget-Friendly Listings)

    • Mostly found in Queens, Staten Island, and parts of Brooklyn.
    • These areas have lower median prices but could be high in demand for budget travelers.

  • Cluster 1 (Mid-Range Investment Areas)

    • Includes Brooklyn and parts of Upper Manhattan.
    • A balanced price-to-demand ratio, making them solid investment choices.

  • Cluster 2 (High-Value Listings)

    • Dominated by Manhattan neighborhoods (Tribeca, SoHo, Midtown, Chelsea).
    • Most expensive properties but with high demand and limited availability.
    • Ideal for luxury Airbnb investments targeting business travelers and high-income tourists.
In [131]:
clustering_data = df[["latitude", "longitude", "price"]].dropna()

clustering_data["price"] = np.log1p(clustering_data["price"])  # Log transformation


# Scaling the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
clustering_data_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(clustering_data)  

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42, n_init=10)
clustering_data["cluster"] = kmeans.fit_predict(clustering_data_scaled) 

custom_palette = {0: "#FF0000",  # Bright Red (Low-Price)
                  1: "#00FF00",  # Neon Green (Mid-Price)
                  2: "#0000FF"}  # Electric Blue (High-Price)


plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
scatter = sns.scatterplot(x=clustering_data["longitude"], y=clustering_data["latitude"], 
                hue=clustering_data["cluster"], palette=custom_palette, alpha=0.6, s=10)



plt.xlabel("Longitude")
plt.ylabel("Latitude")
plt.title("Airbnb Investment Clusters in NYC (Low, Mid, High Pricing)")

labels = ["0: Low-Price", "1: Mid-Price", "2: High-Price"]

handles, _ = scatter.get_legend_handles_labels()
plt.legend(handles=handles, labels=labels, title="Cluster (Investment Category)", 
           markerscale=2, fontsize=12)  
plt.show()

Demand Analysis Using Reviews Per Month¶

We also plotted demand intensity using the number of reviews per month, which serves as a proxy for booking frequency. The heatmap shows:

  • Highly reviewed listings are concentrated in Brooklyn, Queens, and parts of Lower Manhattan.
  • Expensive areas like Midtown Manhattan have fewer reviews, possibly due to lower affordability despite high desirability.
  • Budget-friendly listings in Queens and Brooklyn seem to attract higher booking frequency, making them profitable despite lower nightly rates.

Final Takeaways for Investment Decisions¶

  1. For High-Value, Long-Term Investments:

    • Focus on Cluster 2 (Midtown, Tribeca, SoHo) where prices are high but stable.
    • These areas have limited availability, ensuring exclusivity and higher margins.

  2. For Affordable, High-Demand Investments:

    • Cluster 0 areas (Queens, Brooklyn outskirts) provide steady income through frequent bookings.
    • Ideal for investors aiming for volume-based profits rather than high per-night charges.

  3. For Balanced Growth:

    • Cluster 1 areas (Brooklyn, Harlem, Upper Manhattan) offer moderate prices and strong demand.
    • A safe, mid-range investment strategy with room for appreciation.
